      "content": "Pilots and maintenance crews follow strict inspection protocols to ensure the pitot tube and its associated systems are clear and functional. Before each flight, pilots perform a pre-flight check that includes inspecting the pitot tube. They look for any visible signs of damage or blockage. Pilots may also use a pitot tube heating system to prevent ice build-up, especially in cold weather.\n\nDuring more thorough maintenance checks, mechanics will inspect the pitot tube for any signs of debris, damage, or wear. They may use specialized tools or borescopes to look inside the tube. If a blockage is detected, they will carefully remove it and clean the tube. Depending on the extent of the issue, the pitot tube might need to be replaced entirely. Regular maintenance and checks help prevent unexpected issues during flight and ensure accurate airspeed readings.",
